Description: Digital photograph (colour); view of painted rock art on a rock face (sandstone?) showing one human figure and five unidentified shapes infilled in light brown. The human figure is central, upright and facing right, bent at the knee and the waist with elbows bent and head thrown forward. Below this is an unidentified rectangular shape, very faded (animal?) and to the right is another, vertical. Above this is another, very faded and to the right of this is another, perhaps a human torso with arms outstretched. To the top right is the largest and most clearly delineated shape, in the form of a cross, with a bulbous top point, perhaps representing a head, and the horizontal points curved down (arms?). Wadi Anak, Egypt. Scanned
Curator's comments: This site is a long, sloping shelter running up and under the protected side of an inselberg.
Acquisition name: Donated by: Trust for African Rock Art
